Exploratory Data Analysis¶

The following function gets the following counts for both the dialogue and the summary: number of words, number of characters, number of sentences, mean number of characters in a word, and mean number of words in a sentence. We expect the number of words, number of characters, and number of sentences to be smaller for sentences, but the mean number of characters in a word and the mean number of words in a sentence probably should not change.

In [13]:
def get_counts(df):
    df_eda = pd.DataFrame()
    for col in categorical_features:
        df_eda[col + "_word_count"] = df[col].apply(lambda x: len(str(x).split()))
        df_eda[col + "_char_count"] = df[col].apply(lambda x: len(str(x)))
        df_eda[col + "_sentence_count"] = df[col].apply(
            lambda x: len(sent_tokenize(str(x)))
        )
        df_eda[col + "_mean_word_length"] = df[col].map(
            lambda x: np.mean([len(word) for word in str(x).split()])
        )
        df_eda[col + "_mean_sentence_length"] = df[col].map(
            lambda x: np.mean([len(sentence) for sentence in sent_tokenize(str(x))])
        )
    return df_eda

In [14]:
def visualize(df, feat):
    col = df[feat]
    fig = make_subplots(
        rows=1, cols=2, subplot_titles=["Box Plot", "KDE Plot"], horizontal_spacing=0.2
    )

    fig.add_trace(go.Box(y=col, name="Box Plot"), row=1, col=1)

    density = gaussian_kde(col)
    x = np.linspace(min(col), max(col), 1000)
    fig.add_trace(go.Scatter(x=x, y=density(x), name="KDE Plot"), row=1, col=2)

    fig.update_layout(
        title={
            "text": f'<b>{feat.replace("_", " ").title()}</b>',
            "y": 0.9,
            "x": 0.5,
            "xanchor": "center",
            "yanchor": "top",
        },
        showlegend=False,
        template=template,
        height=600,
        width=800,
    )

    fig.update_yaxes(
        title_text=f"<b>{feat.split('_')[-1].title()}</b>", row=1, col=1, showgrid=True
    )
    fig.update_xaxes(title_text="", row=1, col=1, showgrid=False)

    fig.update_yaxes(title_text="<b>Frequency</b>", row=1, col=2, showgrid=False)
    fig.update_xaxes(
        title_text=f"<b>{feat.split('_')[-1].title()}</b>", row=1, col=2, showgrid=True
    )

    return fig


for feat in df_train_eda.columns:

The following code will draw the correlation matrices for unigrams, bigrams, and trigrams.

In [15]:
def plot_correlation(df, title, cmap):
    """
    This function plots correlation map among features in the dataset.

    Parameters:
    height = Define height
    width = Define width
    font_size = Define the font size for the annotations
    """
    corr = np.round(df.corr(numeric_only=True), 2)

    mask = np.triu(np.ones_like(corr, dtype=bool))
    corr_masked = corr.mask(mask)
    z = corr_masked.values

    # z = corr.values
    for i in range(len(z)):
        for j in range(len(z[0])):
            if i == j:
                z[i][j] = np.nan

    fig = ff.create_annotated_heatmap(
        z=z,
        x=corr.columns.tolist(),
        y=corr.index.tolist(),
        colorscale=cmap,
        showscale=True,
        xgap=1,
        ygap=1,
        zmin=-1,
        zmax=1,
    )

    fig.update_xaxes(side="bottom")

    fig.update_layout(
        title={
            "text": f"<b>{title}</b>",
            "y": 0.9,
            "x": 0.5,
            "xanchor": "center",
            "yanchor": "top",
        },
        margin=dict(t=210, l=110),
        yaxis=dict(autorange="reversed", showgrid=False),
        xaxis=dict(showgrid=False),
        template=template,
        height=800,
        width=800,
    )

    for i in range(len(fig.layout.annotations)):
        fig.layout.annotations[i].font.size = 12
        if fig.layout.annotations[i].text == "nan":
            fig.layout.annotations[i].text = ""

    return fig

We are using TfidfVectorizer to transform our dataset. Note that TfidfVectorizer is just CountVectorizer followed by TfidfTransformer. Using stop_words='english' removes words like 'and' or 'the' that are probably uninformative.

            max_features=15, stop_words="english", ngram_range=(n, n)
        )  # Top 15 terms
        x = vectorizer.fit_transform(df_train[feat])
        df_tfidfvect = pd.DataFrame(
            x.toarray(), columns=vectorizer.get_feature_names_out()
        )
        fig = plot_correlation(
            df_tfidfvect,
            title=feat.title() + " " + str(n) + "-Gram Correlation",
            cmap="Blues",
        )
        fig.show()

There are some phrases that are slightly correlated. For example, "wants buy" and "buy new" has a correlation of 0.14 in the Summary 2-Gram, possibly due to phrases like "...wants to buy a new..." In the Summary 3-Gram, "year eve party" and "new year eve" has a relatively high correlation of 0.25.

There are also tags like <file_other>. We need to remove all expressions of the form <some_string>. We can do this using the re package. In particular, expressions of the form <some_string> can be represented by the regular expression <.*?>, where . matches any character except newline and *? is a non-greedy way of capturing repetitions.

But note that if we only clean <.*?>, then the string Leon: <file_photo> in the first example above would turn into an empty dialogue Leon: . We should clean these as well. The regular expression for strings of the form some_string: is ^[^:\n]+:\s*$, where ^[^:\n]+ matches one or more characters excluding : and newline, \s* matches any whitespace, and $ denotes the end of the string.

We can do this using the following function:

In [20]:
def remove_tags(text):
    tags = re.compile('<.*?>')
    text_no_tags = re.sub(tags, "", text)
    cleaned_text = '\n'.join([line for line in text_no_tags.split('\n') if not re.match(r'^[^:\n]+:\s*$', line)])

    return cleaned_text

In [22]:
def clean_df(df, cols):
    for col in cols:
        df[col] = df[col].fillna('').apply(remove_tags)
    return df

Presumably, Leon showed Arthur a relevant screenshot. It will be interesting to see if the model can still infer this from the dialogue.

Pre-Trained Model¶

As in the tutorial, we will be using a version of BART that has been trained on news articles for summarization, provided here: bart-large-xsum. For inference, we can use the pipeline wrapper from Hugging Face, as follows:

In [27]:
from transformers import pipeline
checkpoint = "facebook/bart-large-xsum"
summarizer = pipeline(
    task='summarization',
    model=checkpoint,
    device=device
)

The second summary is completely unrelated to the corresponding dialogue. Hopefully, fine-tuning can improve the performance of the model.

            (k_proj): Linear(in_features=1024, out_features=1024, bias=True)
            (v_proj): Linear(in_features=1024, out_features=1024, bias=True)
            (q_proj): Linear(in_features=1024, out_features=1024, bias=True)
            (out_proj): Linear(in_features=1024, out_features=1024, bias=True)
          )
          (encoder_attn_layer_norm): LayerNorm((1024,), eps=1e-05, elementwise_affine=True)
          (fc1): Linear(in_features=1024, out_features=4096, bias=True)
          (fc2): Linear(in_features=4096, out_features=1024, bias=True)
          (final_layer_norm): LayerNorm((1024,), eps=1e-05, elementwise_affine=True)
        )
      )
      (layernorm_embedding): LayerNorm((1024,), eps=1e-05, elementwise_affine=True)
    )
  )
  (lm_head): Linear(in_features=1024, out_features=50264, bias=False)
)

Note that BartForConditionalGeneration has a language modeling head for token generation, whereas BartModel just ends with a layer norm. Because our task is seq2seq, we want BartForConditionalGeneration.

We now need to preprocess and tokenize our data before feeding it to the BART model.

In [38]:
print(tokenizer.model_max_length)

1024

Note that the maximum number of tokens allowed by our tokenizer is 1024. So we need to deal with samples where the text is longer than 1024 tokens. The easiest fix is to truncate to the maximum length allowed. This is useful if the beginning of the text is most important. For dialogues, this may not be the best approach (since important information could be at the end of the dialogue), but we will use truncation for now. (An alternative method could be to divide the dialogue into chunks, and summarize in two steps. It would be interesting to explore this idea later.)

In [39]:
def preprocess_function(examples):
    inputs = [doc for doc in examples["dialogue"]]
    model_inputs = tokenizer(inputs, max_length=1024, truncation=True)

    labels = tokenizer(text_target=examples["summary"], max_length=128, truncation=True)

    model_inputs["labels"] = labels["input_ids"]
    return model_inputs

Then to apply the preprocessing function over the entire dataset, we can use the map method.

In [40]:
tokenized_train = ds_train.map(preprocess_function, batched=True, remove_columns=ds_train.column_names)
tokenized_val = ds_val.map(preprocess_function, batched=True, remove_columns=ds_val.column_names)
tokenized_test = ds_test.map(preprocess_function, batched=True, remove_columns=ds_test.column_names)

For seq2seq tasks, we need to use the DataCollatorForSeq2Seq utility in Hugging Face to prepare batches of data for our model. This utility also dynamically pads the inputs received, which is more efficient than padding the whole document to the maximum length, according to the Hugging Face tutorial.

In [42]:
from transformers import DataCollatorForSeq2Seq

Evaluation Metrics¶

In [43]:

rouge = evaluate.load("rouge")

We will use the ROUGE (Recall-Oriented Understudy for Gisting Evaluation) score as our evaluation metric. (Note that this is also the suggested metric in (Hugging Face)[https://huggingface.co/tasks/summarization] for summarization tasks.)

In [45]:
def compute_metrics(eval_pred):
    predictions, labels = eval_pred
    decoded_preds = tokenizer.batch_decode(predictions, skip_special_tokens=True)
    labels = np.where(labels != -100, labels, tokenizer.pad_token_id)
    decoded_labels = tokenizer.batch_decode(labels, skip_special_tokens=True)

    decoded_preds = ["\n".join(nltk.sent_tokenize(pred.strip())) for pred in decoded_preds]
    decoded_labels = ["\n".join(nltk.sent_tokenize(label.strip())) for label in decoded_labels]

    result = rouge.compute(predictions=decoded_preds, references=decoded_labels, use_stemmer=True)

    prediction_lens = [np.count_nonzero(pred != tokenizer.pad_token_id) for pred in predictions]
    result["gen_len"] = np.mean(prediction_lens)

    return {k: round(v, 4) for k, v in result.items()}
